:INFO
The Novel That Swallowed a Whole Weekend
I picked up Pachinko on a Friday evening with the intention of reading one chapter. \
Min Jin Lee's multigenerational story of a Korean family in Japan spans eight \
decades and four generations and does not once let you look away. By Saturday \
afternoon I was rationing chapters to make it last. By Sunday I had finished it \
and felt the particular loss that comes after a very good long novel ends.

:NOW
Thinking about the fourth generation's silence at the novel's end

:QUOTE [subtitle:Min Jin Lee, quotetype:PLAIN]
History has failed us, but no matter.

:JOURNEY
Reading Pachinko
Part
Impact
- Sunja's opening | 5 | Strongest start | One of the best opening acts in modern fiction
- Japan years | 5 | Undeniable weight | Generational burden becomes impossible to ignore
- Mozasu and Solomon | 4 | Less urgent | Later but rewarding if you stay with it
- Final chapters | 4 | Restrained trust | Ending that trusts the reader completely

